 She fell in love with neurosurgery when she read about American doctor Ben Carson's exploits when he successfully separated conjoined twins.  "As a doctor, I enjoy being able to help people when they are most vulnerable. Nothing is more rewarding than a patient coming into the hospital in severe pain or with a marked disability and after intervention and rehabilitation, seeing them smile because they can now walk without pain or they can return to work and lead a normal life," she said.  But as rewarding as her feat is, Shezi admits the neurosurgery was still a male-dominated sector and hard to crack for women. 